name: Tailwind
comment:
A small library that makes using [tailwind.css](https://tailwindcss.com/docs/what-is-tailwind/) a little easier and a little safer to use within Elm.

You'll find classes responding to Tailwind rules in Tailwind.Classes.

In there you'll also find functions for appending responsive qualifiers to those classes. Here's an example of what a div using tailwind might look like:

        div
            [ tailwind
                <| withClasses [ "__login_page" ] -- __login_page is not a tailwind class, it's just for marking the div's purpose.
                <| [ m_1, lg m_6 ]
            ]

@docs stylesheet, tailwind, withClasses, asClasses

values.name: asClasses
values.comment: Turns tailwind classes into normal strings, for when you just want a list of strings instead of an Html.Attribute.

values.name: stylesheet
values.comment: An HTML "link" tag that will import the default tailwind stylesheet

values.name: tailwind
values.comment: A convenience function for specifying classes as a list of strings

values.name: withClasses
values.comment:
A convenience function for adding non-tailwind classes to an element alongside other tailwind classes.
Could be used like this:

    div
        [ tailwind
            <| withClasses [ "superfunclass" ]
            <| [ sm mt_1 ]
        ]
values.type: List String -> List Tailwind.Classes.TailwindClass -> List Tailwind.Classes.TailwindClass

name: Tailwind.Classes

types.name: TailwindClass
types.comment: A type to help make sure we're passing Tailwind classes to the classes function, and not classes for some other CSS utility library. (Can help with refactoring)
